          <h2>Causes & Risk Factors</h2>
          <p align="justify">
          Our body tends to store excess calories in the form of fats. When the intake of calories is more than they are burnt through daily routine activities and exercise; these extra calories cause obesity. It happens commonly due to sedentary lifestyle:<br>
- Eating more than required<br>
- Little or no exercise<br>
- Unhealthy diet and dietary habits- eating fast food, skipping breakfast, heavy meals esp. at night, high calorie food and beverage intake, etc.<br>
- Excessive alcohol intake
 <br><br>
There are other factors which affect metabolism and cause obesity. These are as follows:<br>
- Bulimia- eating disorder<br>
- Psychological complaints like depression, stress, anxiety, etc.<br>
- PCOD<br>
- Cushing syndrome<br>
- Hypothyroidism<br>
- Medicines such as birth control pills, antidepressants, steroids, anti seizure medicines, antipsychotics, etc.<br>
- Lack of sleep for prolonged duration<br>
- Arthritis or other orthopedic disorders that cause reduced movements<br>
- Pregnancy<br>
- Menopause
 <br><br>
 Risk factors for obesity:<br>
<b>- Age:</b> risk for obesity increases as we age. This is occurs from reduced metabolism and digestive power with increasing age.<br>
<b>- Gender:</b> women are more prone to get obese than men. Pregnancy and menopause lead to hormonal changes in women that have additional risk in women for obesity as compared to men.<br>
<b>- Genetics:</b> genes are responsible for metabolism and fat deposition in body. It is the main difference between normal and obese person who eat similar amount of food.<br>
<b>- Family lifestyle:</b> eating habits and family lifestyle is also responsible for obesity.<br>
<b>- Syndrome X:</b> it consists of obesity, hypertension, diabetes and Hyperlipidemia. This runs in families and thus passes obesity and other disease in generations.</p>
